s © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from any of several places called with Old English <i>scīr</i> ‘bright, clear’ + <i>burna</i> ‘stream’, including Sherburn in Elmet (Yorkshire), Sherburn (East Yorkshire, Durham), Shirburn (Oxfordshire), Sherborne (Dorset, Gloucestershire), Sherborne Saint John, Monk Sherborne (Hampshire), Sherbourne (Warwickshire), Sherbourne in Albury (Surrey), and Sherborne in Litton (Somerset). This surname is now rare in Britain."],"variants":[{"name":"Sherburn","meanings":["English: variant of   Sherburne  ."]},{"name":"Sherbon","meanings":["English: variant of   Sherburne   with loss of the second <i>-r-</i> by dissimilation. This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":2,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Richard Sherburne was born in 1335, in Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England, his father, Sir John Sherburne, was 25 and his mother, Margaret Heppall, was 26. He married Alice Plumpton in 1352, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died in 1367, in his hometown, at the age of 32."},"et":{"1335–1367":"1335–1367","–1356":"–1356","1335–1408":"1335–1408","1359–1390":"1359–1390","–Female":"Surnud","1311–1356":"1311–1356","1309–1391":"1309–1391","1352":"1352","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1337":"1337","1359":"1359","1335":"1335","1367":"1367","1356":"1356","1311":"1311","1453":"1453","about 1359":"umbes 1359","about 1356":"umbes 1356","1309":"1309","1408":"1408","1847":"1847","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England, UK":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England":"Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1335–1367":"1335–1367","–1356":"–1356","1335–1408":"1335–1408","1359–1390":"1359–1390","–Female":"Kuollut","1311–1356":"1311–1356","1309–1391":"1309–1391","1352":"1352","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1337":"1337","1359":"1359","1335":"1335","1367":"1367","1356":"1356","1311":"1311","1453":"1453","about 1359":"noin 1359","about 1356":"noin 1356","1309":"1309","1408":"1408","1847":"1847","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England","Lan